My Shimano M485 had one of the pistons quite stuck, which resulted in one of the brake pads being completely worn out rather quickly.

I used this to keep the other piston (the one that still moved) in place and to then exert pressure on the one that was stuck. It didn't take much effort to get it un-stuck, but it will still need some further work to get back to being smooth.

At least on M485 the pistons are not right in the middle of the brake pads so the space for the piston is a bit too wide but the supports were strong enough for me. I might make an optimized version at some point and mirror it.

I printed this at 50% cubic infill and 4 layers, but I guess 100% would be more sturdy.

I would assume this works for any Shimano / Tektro that uses B01S size brake pads.

Please be aware: If the piston is very stiff you may have some problems pushing it back. If that is the case then you may not be able to remove this un-stucker very easily.

This was made for a Panto in the UK,

There is space inside the hollow gem to take two led's in series I chose to salvage a couple of white ones from a cheap torch/flashlight.
All of the parts should fit together as shown in the pictures.

The part labelled switch stopper is optional and simply prevents the switch pushing back inside the ring body when the button is pressed.

The battery contacts are simply made from the legs of a capacitor quite thick, 0.8mm 0.03in and should be bent to fit, with a slight hump where the contact with the battery is made, I think the pictures show this.

The wires can be super glued in place as should the non contact parts of the battery contacts.

I found the best orientation for the batteries was positive down and is wired accordingly.
Ignore the orientation of the batteries in the picture with the ring showing IKEA on the top, they should be IKEA side down.

I used a switch salvaged from an old monitor control panel, you may have to find something similar, The printed power button simply glues onto the switch when it is place.

The printed layer immediately above the switch may not print at all, it's very thin, but is not important.

The ring takes two CR 2032 batteries in a slide out tray. The tray has a small angled groove on top to allow you to get a grip on the battery tray.

I found that putting the batteries in backwards by accident seems to do no harm to the led's

I covered my LED's with a see through red sweet wrapper.

Coloured LED's should be an option, just be sure not to overload them if they cannot take 3v each.

Important note!!:- The battery assembly will provide 6 volts, so make sure the combination of LED's you use can handle this.

I used a natural PLA filament for the gem and gold for most of the rest of the parts.
I would recommend a 0.1mm layer height for most parts. I'll leave you to make your own choices with the rest of the settings.

This is quite a big ring, and the switch I used was intended for manual operation.
You could feed wires into the ring through the switch hole if you wanted to use an external battery supply.
Enjoy!

Shameless plug, Ikea sell these CR 2032 very cheaply, about £1 for 8 in the uk.

These are printable alignment blocks for leveling your X-Gantry on the CR-10 prior to leveling bed.

The long X-gantry is known to go out of level over time, whether this is due to stepper slip, roller creep, stress on axis when changing filament, what ever, it happens.
A parallel axis to the base frame is crucial so when you do level your bed, the prints come out vertical and not skewed.

Follow these instructions for use.

(all movements from control panel unless otherwise stated)

  1. Home Machine
  2. Move Z up about 30 mms or more

  3. Move X over about 40 mms or more

  4. place alignment blocks into position on frame of machine paying attention that the left block has a cut away for the Z-stop switch. Make sure the rails of the blocks fit into the grooves in the aluminum frame.

  5. Move your Z axis slowly until the X-Gantry just about touches Left or Right tops of Alignment Blocks.
    (make a note of how far off the other was for future reference if you like)

  6. Disable steppers from control panel.

  7. Manually screw the Z screws until X-Gantry sits snuggly on both alignment blocks.

  8. Use your control Panel to raise your Z 10mms or more

  9. Remove and store your alignment blocks for later use.

  10. Now follow good bed level procedure to level bed and you are good to go!

Video: https://youtu.be/MNIYfNr9g1I

comments.text:
Sure, first using your control panel, raise your Z up to about 30, move your X over toward the middle.
Put both blocks in place at bottom front of each vertical Z post.
Using control panel lower Z slowly until at least one side just touches the blocks,
If both sides touch together your X gantry is level to your frame.
If one side only touches, disable steppers and release the top screws of the coupling at the base of the Z screw drive that was not touching. The bar should drop down a bit to sit on block, make sure its not touching the bottom stepper shaft. Retighen the screws and using the control panel raise your Z up a hair to release blocks, and your gantry is level

comments.text: In a Dual Z set-up, it's not that the steppers "realign" themselves, it's that spring in the X Gantry (and/or gravity pulling more on the heavier side) will cause the steppers to rotate to a position of balance on their own when disengaged.

Update: Use the 10mm version with 3/8" threaded rod and nuts if you can't get hold of M8 in your area.

description.text: Laser stungun from Space:1999. The stun/kill setting switch is optional, allowing you to make the Mark I or Mark II design. The original model follows the plans slavishly for as exact a replica as possible, while I find the revised gun body a bit less clunky.

Print the gun body upside down. This puts the top of the gun against the build platform and minimizes the need for support. The trigger button can print without support and is glued into the slot on the top. This is all that's required for the Mk I.  
For a Mk II gun with the stun/kill switch, print the carriage and one of the two slider styles. Use a color printer to make the STUN/KILL label for the inside of the carriage. Insert the slider and glue the carriage to the top of the gun.  
Painting:  
1) Start with a glossy black base coat. Make sure all the plastic is well-covered and the paint is completely dry before continuing.  
2) Mask off the black parts of the gun: the handgrip, the trigger button, the hook at the bottom front, and four boxes on each side. Use pinstripe tape to mask off the black lines on the side of the body.  
3) Paint with sliver metallic spray paint. This can be done fairly lightly, as the black base coat will enhance the metallic look on the textured plastic.  
4) Remove the tape and paint the remaining boxes and the knob using a small brush and colorful acrylic paint.  
When making the Mk II gun it can be useful to paint before assembling the slider to avoid getting paint on the moving parts.

作品的形狀是一面是弧面，一面是平面，像餅乾一樣。詳細比例我沒有太介意，大致上身體是圓的，四肢小一點，然後五官比較集中。顏色的話，身體部分是咖啡色，四肢和眼睛眉毛嘴巴是黑色，牙齒是白色。我覺得蠻不滿意作品的，身體的顏色可以再淺一點，下次可以多加點白色進去。

我把嘴巴的部分挖空了，然後加上牙齒嵌進去。四肢本來是比較尖的，建模時改成了半圓形，也把手腳的位置移動了一下。顏色部分，身體改成淺棕色，四肢由本來的黑色改成深棕色。 嘴巴的部分是我認為最複雜的。我把圓形屋頂嵌進身體（半圓球）中，再把它調成孔（透明）。再放進去一個白色方塊，當作牙齒。 醫療：一個年僅5歲的英國小女孩，在出生時左手五指是發育不完全的。利用這個女孩父母提供的塑膠模型，再透過3D列印技術的幫助，女孩獲得了「人工手」。 建築：建築師的客戶通常會需要從空間各個可能的角度檢視產品，來得到一個清晰的印象，以做出修改。利用3D列印技術，建築師就不用再手工建造模型，可以節省時間和人力。 教育：3D列印讓學生可以不再使用傳統方法製作模型，而是利用3D技術直接設計和列印模型。一堂課的時間通常不常，3D列印可以有效縮短製作時間，讓學生可以花更多時間思考創新。 因為它很可愛！雖然我做出來不是很可愛還有點醜，但因為角色原型是可愛的所以印下來吧。

用白色的黏土揉成兩個圓圓的球，讓比較大的那個墊在下面，再拿非常少黑色黏土揉成兩個小黑點當作它的眼睛，最後再多揉兩個小黑點黏在它的身體上就像是有穿衣服。
你對於作品感到滿意嗎？哪裡還有進步的空間呢？
不是很滿意，雖然它看起來很可愛，但製作方法有點太簡單，或許我可以再多想想，有什麼東西可以做得比較複雜，或者是做得更精緻一點。

請描述從黏土到建模時，你在設計上的修正（可能是小部份或是置換大主題） 因為我認為雪人實在是太單調了，想要做些更有技術性的東西，所以我選擇蓋了一棟房子。 tinkerCAD軟體的哪一項功能最吸引你？讓你感到驚艷？ 我覺得每個功能都讓我感到新奇，畢竟這是我第一次在電腦上接觸３Ｄ創作，如果真要選一個的話，我覺得拉著那個黑色的像是三角形的鍵，就可以讓它變高或變低，而且不會變形非常的酷，雖然它只是一個基本功能，卻也是一個非常重要的功能，但我覺得有點難操作，很容易就不小心太高或太低。 在你的設計作品中，描述一個最複雜的結構，並試圖描述它是由哪些向量幾合構成的？ 我想應該是窗戶吧，先拉一個正方體出來，再拉四個小正方體，把它們調成透明的，塞到大正方體裡面，上下距離要調好，畢竟要讓它穿透過去，小正方體也要各自對齊，才會像是窗戶，最後在全部合併。 3D列印的生活應用層面，試圖以醫療、建築、和教育三大面向給予描述。 ３Ｄ列印讓義肢與輔助器具的價格變得便宜，使更多的人能夠承受，而在醫美的方面，電腦動畫模擬結合全彩３Ｄ列印設備，能讓客戶先看到手術後的樣貌，再做決定，至於外科手術的方面，３Ｄ列印能夠將斷層掃描的資料印出，對於醫師進行術前模擬有很大的幫助。 運用在建築方面的話，不僅價格較低，完工速度很快，甚至還能夠客製化。 ３Ｄ列印進入教育的話，能夠讓學生更有興趣在課程上，甚至是親自動手做，讓學生更能夠吸收。

黏土創作設計概念
請試圖描述作品的形狀、比例、顏色
米奇的頭就是用三個圓組成的，眼睛白色、黑色的部分是用橢圓形捏。嘴巴的地方，因為我想要捏一個愛心的形狀，手拙的我想要捏出愛心，真的是費了我不少時間，不過做出來的愛心其實還不錯看。在他嘴巴那邊白色尖尖的部份我也捏了很久才有一個類似的圖形，米奇組成的顏色是我很喜歡的三個顏色：黑、白、紅，所以在捏黏土的時候我非常期待自己做出來的成品。
你對於作品感到滿意嗎？哪裡還有進步的空間呢？
　　　我非常喜歡我最後做出來的成品，雖然跟別人比起來，我幾乎不用使用到什麼技巧，但我覺得這是我做過的黏土作品中最好的一個。我的黏土作品其實每一個都是米奇，但這樣可以知道每一個時期的我都在進步，每一次的作品都一次一次的提升，我覺得我在做耳朵這方面可以再進步，因為我很常做出一對不符合比例的耳朵，不然就是太扁或是太圓，總是沒辦法很剛好的抓到整體的比例。

3D建模tinkerCAD 請描述從黏土到建模時，你在設計上的修正（可能是小部份或是置換大主題） 　　　對我來說我覺得做建模比起捏黏土簡單，因為我的圖形都是基本的幾何圖形所以電腦可以用數字調整出我想要的形狀、比例，比起使用黏土捏製，用電腦更精準。從黏土到建模，我把嘴巴白色的部分做得更像，尖的地方可以做得更細緻。 tinkerCAD軟體的哪一項功能最吸引你？讓你感到驚艷？ 　　　他有很多特殊的造型，雖然我的作品不需要太過奇特的圖形，但我覺得可以做出如此酷炫的圖形超讚的，還有他可以藉由結合兩種不一樣圖形來創造我們想要的圖形，這個也非常的新奇，這一個程式對我來說是一個新的體驗 在你的設計作品中，描述一個最複雜的結構，並試圖描述它是由哪些向量幾合構成的？ 　　　嘴巴愛心的地方是整個作品裡最複雜的地方，他需要三角形和圓形合成那個形狀，這個地方我花了很多的時間製作，也試了很多次，最後才做出一個了勉強可以看的愛心。 3D列印的生活應用層面，試圖以醫療、建築、和教育三大面向給予描述。 在建築方面：3D列印，可以理解為增材製造，運用高分子材料、金屬、複合材料等多種材料構成實物的一種技術。3D列印可以精準將材料放置於需要的地方，以減少材料浪費並以更快的速度生產低量結構。3D列印在其他行業也發揮著重要作用，而且許多專家認為3D列印在不久的將來將成為建築工程行業的實用工具之一。建築物已成為投資組合的一部分。現在建築工程領域的許多3D列印應用如室內裝飾和照明器件都已商業化。與此同時，還存在著開發合適材料、遵守建築法規等諸多挑戰，當然也有諸多機遇，如節約建築時間、增加設計靈活性等。

I was printing a mobile weather station when I came across this challenge and I thought that wouldn't it be cool to check the weather up high or any area really? But I couldn't stop there. The great thing is I added some template stl's so additional accessories can be designed and added.

tinkerCAD軟體的哪一項功能最吸引你？讓你感到驚艷？ 可以拼接出各種不同的形狀，做出各種你想得到的東西，甚至是建築模型。操作上也很容易，只要有gmail、會用滑鼠基本上就可以用了。而且他提供很多特殊造型給用戶使用，省下很多座圖形的時間。還可以把做好的立體作品轉換成用樂高積木堆疊的模樣很新奇。 在你的設計作品中，描述一個最複雜的結構，並試圖描述它是由哪些向量幾合構成的？ 中間心型的類似階梯狀的凹槽。是一個很扁的圓形中間用核心的造型鏤空再切割出空心的圖形對其拼接。都是用核心的圖形反覆鏤空拼接。

3D列印的生活應用層面，試圖以醫療、建築、和教育三大面向給予描述。  醫療:     1. 手術: 利用3D列印重建模擬的方式，在實際動手術之前就可以模擬手術的過程，大幅降低臨床失敗機率，提高醫師手術之效率及精準度並減少手術時間提昇復原品質，使用親和人體組織的金屬3D列印，可減少排斥與感染的發生率。另外，醫美診所透過彩色3D列印模擬手術後的樣貌，減少患者術前焦慮感。 2. 3D列印義肢: 告別傳統石膏與笨重義肢，輕薄、透氣、合身客製化的3D列印義肢已成為醫療主流。 3.可以做出器官模型，也被應用在植牙、聽力輔助、義肢、藥物甚至人體皮膚上。經過多年發展，成本降低、品質也提升。以前只能使用一、兩種材料，做出一兩種顏色，現在可以同時做出六種材料，還能滿足超過36萬種材質和顏色的需求，無論是軟組織還是骨頭都能更精準模擬。  建築: 目前已有再24小室內用3D列印出一棟房屋的案例。以往在建材方面是整個建造過程中最耗心力及金錢的地方，但現在這個技術可以解決耗時耗材耗資源的問題，除了環境因素，無論是用印製零件再組裝液或直接用水泥印出一棟房屋對我們來說都會更方便，改變大眾對於房屋建造不能同時達成快速、環境友善、有效率的印象，解決全球居住問題，可以用於急需大量快速建造房屋的區域，或是重建遭天災摧毀的房子。  教育: 3D列印技術能實現虛擬世界與實體世界的有機結合，3D印表機將使得學生在創新能力和動手實踐能力上得到訓練，將學生的創意、想像變為現實，將極大發展學生動手和動腦的能力，從而實現學校培養方式的變革。3D列印課程同時擁有視覺和觸覺的學習方式，具有很強的誘惑力，在觸覺學習中，學生不是在黑板或顯示器上簡單地看文字或 圖形，而是通過他們的觸覺抓住核心概念的三維模型，這樣能夠吸收和消化知識，使學生在學習中獲得更多樂趣並將所學印象深刻記在腦中。

description.text:
1/1/2018 Update: Well, Version 2.1 was a bust, but here's version 2.2
Extended the walls to cover part of the fan housing and use the notches on the fan housing to hold it together without extra screws (or loctite). Now easier to remove and lube the fan.
Extended the nozzles closer to the extruder nozzle for more even cooling, wasn't getting cooled on the front side, now it works great.
Will mark complete, but may still make changes. FreeCAD file is included for your entertainment. What's more entertaining than changing things.

Update: Version 2 updated. Much bigger, more robust version. Thicker walls. Cleaned it up quite a bit.
Will post pictures and clean up the FreeCAD file before making it "Finished".

Uses a 5015 Blower, like this one on Amazon.

After downloading lots of fan ducts, I found they all crashed my printer because of to much cooling on the heater block (need to turn down the blower to prevent). I designed this to run fine with the blower at 100%. Got the fan duct as short as possible and as close to the nozzle as possible.

Also makes it much easier to remove the blower's motor and impeller to clean and oil. Something I found needs to be done fairly often. (but they do last, if you keep them clean)

The fan is blowing mostly down, but because of the shape, the air is being dragged toward the nozzle. You can hear it clearly when the duct passes over a hollow shape.

There are 4 .stl files.
WD6FanTop_StudsBlower.stl is a single print file and a single part to install.
WD6Blower.stl is just the blower duct.
WD6FanTop_Studs.stl is just the fan cover with mounting studs.
WD6FanTop_NoStuds.stl is the fan cover without mounting studs.

The FreeCAD file is also included so you can do what you want with it.
(noncommercial, share alike)

I do not take donations. If you print, use and are happy with this design, show your appreciation by posting your make, giving feedback and improving this design.

Notes:

Supports ONLY from the build plate. Don't clog your duct with stuff you can't remove. The bridges it will have to print should be minor enough to work, otherwise, print one and use it to print a better one.
Highest temp plastic you can use, I used eSun PLA+, but ABS will work. Standard PLA will not survive that close to the heater block.
If PLA+ fails, I'll try in ABS.
Update: PLA+ warped when printing ABS. Switched to ABS and a screw fell out, crashing things into everything and broke the duct, I'm printing a new one.
Do NOT let your fan stop. It will warp the nozzle. Easy to take the blower motor and impeller off to clean and lube.

Update: USE THREAD LOCK I've had issues with the screws falling out.

Remove the supports.
Remove the old fan/blower and ducts.
Use 2 counter-sink screws to screw the newly printed fan top to two of the mounting holes. (back left and front right)
Remove the top cover from a 5015 blower.
Use a much longer screw to screw the blower's motor half, through the new fan top to the 3rd mounting hole. (back right)
Use another screw and nut through the blower and fan top.
Make sure everything is snug. You might see daylight through near the corner where the nozzle is, but it will blow plenty of air. I'm still tweaking the design.

This is the extruder used on the Griffin Delta printer, and one without mounting ears. It allows the use of geared and normal Nema 17 stepper motors (see the instructions for the geared stepper it fits) as well as several bowden options. Features:
Uses little plastic
Easy to clean, exposed hob
One side allows for a feeder tube or bowden
While the other side uses a screw on cap, which makes for easy removal of bowden tubes as well as allowing for the use of a 4mm captive nut instead of a pneumatic fitting. This whole assembly can be cut off if not wanted. *To use the nut, you need to break off the inner ring under the screw on cap to make room for the nut. See the Griffin here:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:259238

No support is needed, it's already built in. Print at 70% infill with PLA. There are several ribs where the idler bearing sits that need to be broken out. There is also a flat area on the bottom of the threaded plastic that needs to be removed in order for the cap to be threaded on. Threads for the Pneumatic fittings and idler bolt are built in, but often need cleaning up. Assembly is pretty straightforward, it can't go together wrong. 1x 625zz bearing (5x16x5mm)
1x Nema17 gear reduced motor http://store.makerstoolworks.com/extruders-and-parts/geared-nema17-stepper-motor/
1x m3x20mm bolt (socket head cap)
1x m3 nut
1x m3 washer (flat)
2x m3x10mm bolt (socket head cap)
1x 8mm I.D. hobbed gear: Trinity Labs, Makertoolworks and Ebay all have them.
1x M5x15mm Socket Head Bolt (14mm-16mm is fine) Optional build (for those on a budget)
Replace the geared motor and hobbed pulley with these. I really prefer the geared setup though.
1x Nema 17 I recommend Kysan for the torque
1x Ultibots 1.75mm hobbed pulley

Assembly
  • There are 2 options for the back cover. Can print the single piece or 2 pieces for Velco ties.
  • Drill the holes to fit the screws in the back, I found 4 screws was sufficient. The back plate as markings for optional 6 screws.
  • Battery space fits CR2 3.0v or any other type of button batteries can also fit in the space, just secure down with craft foam.
  • Cut 2 pieces of small foam and double side tape them to each end of the battery compartment.
  • Optionally, used double sided tape on the front cover LED reflector and then gilded with tin foil using a cotton swab to get everything smooth. Then cut a CD case to make a lense and taped the lense in place.
  • The battery connectors were wrapped with tin foil along with a small piece of copper wire.
  • Bend LED legs 90 degrees -> wire negative battery connector to 1 connector of the push button then on other side of push button connect a wire to negative leg of LED then on the positive leg of LED wired to positive battery connector. Please consult google for wiring as I'm no expert.
  • Once wiring is all done, use double sided tape on back of each battery connector and secure to each side of the foam. Push the LED and push button into place along with all the wiring.
  • Insert battery and test. Secure the back plate(s). Decorate lamp as needed.

description.text:
After printing off some minis I noticed that my dwarves were too tall, so I made this handy tool. Drop it on the build plate next to your model and it will tell you how tall it is in 28mm scale.

BE SURE TO ADJUST FOR BASE HEIGHT!

In 28mm scale, 1 inch = 5 feet (1:60 ratio), therefore the numbers come out as;

1 foot = 5.08 mm
2 feet = 10.16 mm (Longsword)
3 feet = 15.24 mm (Gnome)
4 feet = 20.32 mm (Halfling)
5 feet = 25.40 mm (Dwarf)
6 feet = 30.48 mm (Human, Elf)
7 feet = 35.56 mm (Orc)

Heights can vary depending on what lore you follow (D&D, LOTR, etc) but the above examples are generally acceptable.

Hopefully this helps someone else out! If you're using a different scale, you can scale the height chart as follows:

10mm 36%
12mm 43%

description.text:
I've always very much liked the Estes Saros rocket for it's sleek scale like appearance. It was available from 1971 - 1978 and is hard to come by.
The kit came with a plastic fin unit, plastic adapter/transition and a plastic nose cone.
A fellow owner of the original Saros was nice enough to send me the dimensions of the parts.

In addition to the original fin unit "Estes_Saros_4Fin_Unit" two modified variants are available:

  • "Estes_Saros_4Fin_Unit_Plate" has the "Foil press on" integrated to the fin unit.
  • "Estes_Saros_3Fin_Unit_Plate" is a 3 fin version with rivets and holding plates.

I've added some pictures to aid in construction. I recommend not to glue the fin unit in place. Friction fit should be sufficient to hold the everything in place. This is so you can swap the fin unit if needed.

You can download the instructions here:

  • Saros: http://plans.rocketshoppe.com/estes/estK-54/estK-54.htm
  • Nomad: http://plans.rocketshoppe.com/estes/est1344/est1344.htm

I would love to see your results!

Leo

Update 22. Nov. 2017

I was able to come across original parts. I've made some changes to the nose cone and the fin units. All parts are now as close to the original as possible.

IMPORTANT

  • Shell thickness must be set to 0.6mm!
  • It's best to print at around 40mm/s.
  • Make sure your printer is well calibrated.

Nosecone:

  • May be printed in PLA but I recommend PETG or ABS.
  • Solid bottom infill must be set.

Adapter:

  • May be printed in PLA but I recommend PETG or ABS.
  • Solid bottom infill must be set.
  • The lower adapter shoulder going into the main BT-50 tube needs to be sanded down until it fits but still has friction. If too loose drag separation will occur!
  • Shell thickness must be set to 0.6mm!
  • Brim is recommended.

Fin unit:

  • Solid top and bottom infill must be unchecked!
  • This part must be printed in PETG or ABS. Tests have shown that PLA will melt around the lower nozzle area.
  • Shell thickness must be set to 0.6mm!
  • Brim is recommended.

comments.text: Stumbled on this project by accident. This is very interesting to me. When I was a kid, I used to launch Estes model rockets over a lake near my Grandmother's house. And then retrieve the rocket via boat. The problem was, the rockets that I made used cardboard for the fuselage. When it splashed down in the lake, it would take me a few minutes to reach the rocket in the boat. By then, the hot rocket would have swelled up inside the cardboard tube and made it nearly impossible to remove without destroying the rocket's tube (dry landings did not have this problem, of course). The lake is really the only clear area for rocket launches, so I sort of gave up on model rocketry after destroying a few of them on their maiden flights.

description.text:
Your very own enclosure for standard HP 2.5" drive sleds that litter the floors of IT workshops the world over.

Easy to print with whatever you've got.

Happy for this to be shared and mangled, then reshared - just point this way for the original credit. Please dont use for commercial profit, this is meant to be shared for free, cos its my first 'meaningful' design and finally am giving back something (very small).

Notes:

Print on end with hole for USB cable. Supports likely needed for sled lock mechanism cut out, I used em. Pick your own resolution/infill...not much open space anyway; mostly walls. I did 3/3/3 perimeters, wouldn't go less than 3 imo.

Use a skirt unless you get legendary adhesion. Its fairly tall so could wobble off on the short edge. I didn't experiment printing in any other orientation.

This was designed for PLA, with my e3d lite hotend I went with 210C and 60C bed temp.

Might be a good one to use up the last dregs of those filament rolls.

I designed this as a present for a departing team member at work. The team pitched in on the 1tb hdd and usb3 to sata adapter, work provided the sled, and I provided the enclosure. We inscribed some text on the exterior, but no text in this model.

Very basic but the dimensions are tight so the drive doesn't rattle and to prevent the sled from falling out. I made several copies of the final design with different PLA reels and found for some I could release the sled easily and others it was very tight. Your mileage for swapability may vary depending on material used.

Takes any normal height and half height hdd - full height (like sas) drives will not fit. If it fits in a normal laptop, it will fit in this.

Completely designed in Tinkercad, with a set of chinesium callipers and a spare sled from work.

USB to sata adapter used is the J5Create JEE252 https://en.j5create.com/products/jee252

...but many different brands are of the same design. Fair bit of room for variance with the large hole for the USB cable.

Could benefit with some support inside for the USB adapter but... should be fine if not abused.

This is a model for a hairy xmas tree. It doesn't need postprocessing after printing as it doesn't use a coaster wall. Filament will hang down during printing due to extrusion temperature. There are some similar models out there but I wanted to design my own.

Recommendations for print: No support required. No postprocessing. Recommended 0.2 layer and 0.4 nozzle. PLA or flex print. No layer fan. Don't scale it down, it won't work as thin layers won't be printed. This is a 2-3 hour print as it is 100x140x140 mm print.

Hint: You can change the filament near the mid of the print to a white one to make it snowy... Or even multicolor ;-)

title: Adapters for Danco 46004 Cross-Arm Faucet Handle
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The shower in my house has weird faucets -- I've never seen anything like them. Neither had the guy at the plumbing supply store.

About nine months ago, one broke (the inside of the plastic handle where it attaches to the faucet stem stripped).

I purchased a "universal" replacement, the Danco 46004 Cross-Arm Faucent Handle, which includes "7 plastic adapters and 1 metal adapter to fit most faucet brands".

But not mine. The provided adapters were all too big.

So I reverse engineered the adapter.

The things provided here all match the Danco adapters externally but the inside hole is a simple cylindrical shape (with a chamfer for mounting) that press fits onto the stem. The number indicates ten times the radius of the inner cylindrical hole.

There are multiples because I wasn't sure what tolerance would work.

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

No

As small as your printer will handle

100%

Notes:

I printed these out of PLA and they worked. Not sure what would happen with a softer and / or harder plastic.

Step 1

Printer a series of adapters and mark them with their size so that you can tell them apart.

Note: If I were to do this again, I would imprint this information on each adapter, but I didn't know how to to that when I created this thing and, with my shower not working, I was in a bit of a rush.

Step 2

Find the smallest adapter that you can fit on the stem by hand.

Step 3

Go 2 sizes smaller (I figured this out the hard way) and use the screw that goes into the center hole of the stem to press it onto the stem.

I found that I had to use several different lengths of screw and the adapters that come with the product as shims to accomplish this.

And plenty of "elbow grease".

Step 4

Take a shower :-)
